        "title": "\ud83c\udf7d\ufe0fFlavorSense: Tastes Predicted by Life & Climate",
        "subtitle": "Classify food tastes using life routines, geography & upbringing cuisine",
        "description": "Dive into a unique synthetic dataset that **predicts food taste preferences**\u2014Spicy, Sweet, Sour, or Salty\u2014based on lifestyle habits, sleep cycles, exercise levels, climate zones, and cultural cuisine exposure. Perfect for classification projects, EDA practice, or building recommendation systems with a flavorful twist!\n\n1.Multi-class Classification: Predict `preferred_taste` using all features.\n\n2.EDA & Visualization: Explore **how lifestyle and climate impact food preferences.**\n\n3.Missing Value Handling: Practice imputation techniques (SimpleImputer, KNN, etc.)\n\n4.Cultural Feature Encoding: Encode `historical_cuisine` creatively (OneHot, Embedding).\n\n5.Model Comparison: Test Decision Trees, SVM, XGBoost, or Neural Nets.\n\n6.Recommendation System: Build a basic taste preference recommender.\n\n=== About this file ===\n\nAbout this file\nShape : 10000 Rows * 6 Columns\nFormate : CSV\nMissing values : Present\n\n\n=== Columns & descriptions ===\n\nage: Age can influence metabolism, taste sensitivity, and food preferences (e.g., younger people may prefer sweeter flavors).\nsleep_cycle: Circadian rhythms and sleep patterns can influence hormone levels, hunger, and cravings.\nexercise_habits: Active people may prefer salty/spicy due to sodium loss from sweating or increased metabolic demand.\nclimate_zone: Climate influences traditional diets. Spicy food is more common in hot and humid climates (e.g., India, Mexico).\nhistorical_cuisine_exposure: Cuisine history reflects taste conditioning\u2014someone exposed to Mediterranean food may prefer salty/sour, while Asian might prefer spicy or umami.\npreferred_taste: preferred_taste: Categorical label with 4 classes \u2013 'Spicy', 'Sweet', 'Sour', 'Salty'\n",
